<!-- RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Koreatown · Korean Fried Chicken Restaurant · Frymaster GF14SD Gas Floor Fryer</div>
        <h3>"Fryer completely dead — not heating at all. Saturday lunch coming up."</h3>
        <p>Tripped hi-limit thermostat on a Frymaster GF14SD gas floor fryer. The previous night shift had allowed the oil level to drop below the minimum line — likely through evaporation and absorption during a long service — and then turned on the fryer without topping up the oil. Running with insufficient oil caused the gas to superheat the bottom of the vat, tripping the hi-limit. The morning kitchen manager called us in a panic at 9am for a 12pm Saturday service.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Arrived within 90 minutes. Located and reset the hi-limit (rear access panel, standard Frymaster location). Tested through one full heat cycle — fryer reached 375°F without hi-limit tripping again. Checked oil level markings, showed kitchen staff the minimum oil fill line and explained the hi-limit trip mechanism. Total time on-site: 45 minutes, no parts needed. Restaurant had time to heat oil and be ready for service. Recommended adding an oil level check to the opening checklist — this was the third hi-limit trip in 8 months for the same reason.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Boyle Heights · Carnitas Restaurant · Pitco SG14S Standing Pilot Gas Fryer</div>
        <h3>"Pilot lights but burners won't come on — fryer just sits there cold"</h3>
        <p>Failed thermocouple on a Pitco SG14S standing-pilot gas fryer in a Boyle Heights carnitas operation. The pilot was lighting normally — the operator could see the flame — but the main burners wouldn't ignite. The thermocouple had weakened to the point where it was generating enough millivoltage to hold the pilot valve open but not enough to open the main gas valve. A classic graduated thermocouple failure that typically presents as "pilot light keeps going out" before it progresses to "pilot lights but nothing else works."</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Measured thermocouple output with millivolt meter — reading 9 mV (minimum 18–20 mV required to hold main valve open). Replaced thermocouple with OEM Pitco replacement. Main burners ignited on first attempt after replacement. Verified all four burner zones through complete heat cycle to 350°F. Cleaned burner ports while on-site — found partial carbon blockage on two ports reducing BTU output, contributing to slow recovery time the operator had been noticing. Carnitas operation fully restored within 2 hours of arrival.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Garden Grove (OC) · Korean Fried Chicken · Pitco E14 Electric Floor Fryer</div>
        <h3>"Oil never gets fully up to temperature — food coming out greasy"</h3>
        <p>Partial electric heating element failure on a Pitco E14 electric floor fryer at a Garden Grove Korean fried chicken operation. One of two heating elements had failed open — generating no heat — while the other continued functioning. The fryer's thermostat read the residual heat from the one working element and cycled normally, but overall heat input was approximately 40% below spec. The result: fryer showed "ready" on the control panel at 325°F but oil temperature measured by a probe was 285–295°F — below the threshold for proper crust formation and drainage, producing greasy chicken with insufficient crust.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Measured element resistance — found one element open circuit (infinity ohms vs. 8–12 ohms for a functional element). Replaced both elements simultaneously — industry practice when one fails on a dual-element fryer, since the second is likely near end of life and replacing both avoids a return service call within months. Verified oil temperature vs. thermostat reading using calibrated probe after repair — 327°F actual vs. 325°F set, within acceptable calibration tolerance. Restaurant confirmed crust quality improvement in the first service after repair.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Westlake Village (Ventura) · Thai Restaurant · Frymaster MJ35 Gas Fryer</div>
        <h3>"Fryer takes forever to recover temperature after we put in food"</h3>
        <p>Clogged burner tubes on a Frymaster MJ35 tube-type gas fryer at a Westlake Village Thai restaurant with partial blockage from carbon and food debris accumulation over approximately 14 months without a service visit. The fryer was reaching operating temperature normally but recovery after a load of food was dropped dramatically — oil temperature falling from 375°F to below 320°F and taking 8+ minutes to recover. In a Thai restaurant running multiple fried items simultaneously, the slow recovery was forcing the kitchen to pace orders and was causing consistency problems in fried food texture.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Removed and cleaned all four burner tubes with commercial kitchen degreaser and wire brush — found significant carbon accumulation at the gas orifice ends of two tubes reducing effective BTU output. Tested BTU output before and after cleaning using temperature recovery rate as proxy — recovery time dropped from 8.5 minutes to 2.5 minutes after cleaning, representing approximately 67% improvement in effective heat delivery. Calibrated thermostat against probe — found it reading 12°F high, adjusted. Restaurant noticed the improvement in service within the first shift. Enrolled in annual maintenance contract.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

